{{Infobox artist | name = Ghisha Koenig | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 8 December 1921 | birth_place = London | death_date = {{Death date and age|1993|10|15|1921|12|8|df=y}} | death_place = | nationality = British | field = Sculpture | training = {{ubl|[[Hornsey School of Art]]|[[Chelsea School of Art]]|[[Slade School of Art]]}} | movement = | works = ''The Machine Minders'' | influences = | influenced = | spouse = }}
'''Ghisha Koenig''' (8 December 1921 - 15 October 1993) was a British sculptor whose work focused on the work place, especially factories as a hub of human activity.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.serpentinegalleries.org/exhibitions-events/ghisha-koenig-sculpture-1968-1986|title=Ghisha Koenig: Sculpture 1968-1986|website=Serpentine Galleries|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref>
== Life == Ghisha Koenig was born in London on 8 December 1921, the daughter of Leo Koenig (1898-1970), art critic and writer, and his wife, Fanny Hildebrand (fl. 1900-1940), formerly a Yiddish actress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/52209|title=Ghisha Koenig|website=www.oxforddnb.com|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref> In 1950, she married Dr. Emanuel (Manny) Tuckman, and they had one daughter, Sarah.<ref name="Independent">The Independent: [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-ghisha-koenig-1511657.html Obituary: Ghisha Koenig - People - News - The Independent], accessdate: 28/08/2014</ref> She died on 15 October 1993.<ref name="Independent" />
== Work == Koenig studied at the [[Hornsey School of Art]], the [[Chelsea School of Art]] with [[Henry Moore]], and the [[Slade School of Art]].<ref name="Foster">{{cite book|last1=Foster|first1=Alicia|title=Tate women artists|date=2004|publisher=Tate|location=London|isbn=9781854373113|page=130}}<!--|accessdate=28 August 2014--></ref> During World War II she was a member of the [[Auxiliary Territorial Service]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url = http://www.worldcat.org/title/writing-on-the-wall-women-writers-on-women-artists/oclc/29701054&referer=brief_results|title = Writing on the wall: women writers on women artists|last = Collins|first = Judith|last2 = Lindner|first2 = Elsbeth|last3 = Tate Gallery|date = 1993-01-01|publisher = Weidenfeld & Nicolson|isbn = 0297813692|location = London|language = English}}</ref> Her first solo exhibition was at the [[Grosvenor Gallery]] in London in 1966. She also had a solo exhibition at the [[Serpentine Galleries|Serpentine Gallery]] in London in 1986. This exhibition included works created from 1968 to 1986 from three series, ''The Glassworks'', ''The Tentmakers'' and ''The Plate and Coil Shop''.<ref name=":1" /> Factories she visited or worked at included [[J & E Hall]], Dartford (APV Products Ltd) which made escalators and salination systems, the Plate and Coil Shop, and the Fettling Shop.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Steyn|first=Juliet|date=1994|title=Juliet Steyn remembers Ghisha Koenig|url=|journal=Women's Art Magazine|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> Many of her sculptures are done in bronze or terracotta bas-reliefs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0012_0_11332.html|title=KOENIG, GHISHA|last=American-Israeli Cooperative Enterprise|first=|date=2013|website=Jewish Virtual Library|publisher=|access-date=March 5, 2015}}</ref>
Her work is in the permanent collection of the [[Tate Gallery]],<ref name=Foster/> the Museum of Labour History in Manchester, Middleheim Museum in Belgium, the Graves Art Gallery in Sheffield, the City Art Gallery in Stoke-on Trent, Homerton College in Cambridge, and the City Art Gallery in Manchester.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |url=http://www.boundarygallery.com/koenig/koenig.html |title=Untitled Document |website=www.boundarygallery.com |access-date=2016-03-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601002123/http://www.boundarygallery.com/koenig/koenig.html |archivedate=2012-06-01 |df= }}</ref> Public commissions include the Ministry of Work, 1950; Festival of Britain, 1951; St. John the Divine, 1961; Dalton House School, Sevenoaks, Kent 1986.<ref name=":2" />
== Exhibitions == * 1953, 1958, 1960, 1963 The Royal Academy * 1958-61 Society of Portrait Sculptors * 1959 Smithsonian Institution, Washington * 1963, 1964, 1966, 1968, [[Grosvenor Gallery]], London * 1974 ''Ghisha Koenig Sculpture 1968-74,'' Bedford House Gallery, London<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artfortune.com/ghisa-koenig/artistbiographies-129457/|title=Ghisa Koenig - Artists - Art Fortune|website=www.artfortune.com|access-date=2016-03-05}}</ref> * 1978 Wins Arts Council Award solo show at Galerie Husstege, Holland * 1986, retrospective solo exhibition at the Serpentine Gallery<ref name="Walls">{{cite book|author=Judith Collins & Elsbeth Lindner (editors)|publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson|year=1993|title= Writing on the Wall, Women Writers on Women Artists|ISBN=0 297 81369 2}}</ref> * 1986, 1994, 2005, 2010 Boundary Gallery, London; * 1993 Tate Gallery, London
