{{mergeto|Nikolai Triik|date=August 2018}} {{expand Estonian|Lennuk (Triik)|date=November 2016}} {{Infobox artwork | title = Lennuk | image = File:Nikolai Triik, Lennuk.jpg | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | painting_alignment = | other_language_1 = Estonian | other_title_1 = Lennuk | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = Nikolai Triik | year = {{start date|1910}} | completion_date = <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | catalogue = | medium = tempera and pastel on paper | material = | subject = Lennuk, the ship of Kalevipoeg | height_metric = 73.8 <!-- (i.e. in metric units) --> | width_metric = 137 | length_metric = | height_imperial = <!-- (i.e. in imperial units) --> | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | diameter_metric = | diameter_imperial = | metric_unit = cm <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | imperial_unit = in <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | dimensions = | dimensions_ref = | condition = | owner = [[Art Museum of Estonia]] | accession = | museum = [[Kumu Art Museum]] | city = [[Tallinn]] | coordinates = <!-- Only use for the coordinates (when known) of the artwork itself, i.e. not for the site, building, structure, etc where it is kept, otherwise leave blank (or omit): {{coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | preceded_by = <!-- preceding work by the same artist --> | followed_by = <!-- next work by the same artist --> | website = <!-- Official webpage/site only: {{URL|example.com}} --> }} '''''Lennuk''''' is a painting by [[Nikolai Triik]] of 1910,<ref name="EKM">[http://kunstimuuseum.ekm.ee/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/ekm_vilnius_rest_2011_margit_a4_est.pdf Eesti Kunstimuuseum: Lennuk] {{et icon}}</ref> depicting Lennuk,<ref>"Lennuk" is also the Estonian word for "aeroplane"</ref> the ship of Kalevipoeg, son of [[Kalevi (mythology)|Kaleva]], from the Estonian national epic ''[[Kalevipoeg]]''.
The work measures 73.8&nbsp;cm by 137&nbsp;cm and is painted in [[tempera]] and pastel on paper.<ref name="EKM" />
It is part of the collection of the [[Art Museum of Estonia]] and is exhibited in the [[Kumu Art Museum]] in [[Tallinn]].<ref name="EKM" />
